---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";

const seo = {
  title: "Humi | Anna Kocaj",
  description:
    "Humi is an AI-powered meeting assistant that helps leaders read their team's emotions in real time.",
  image: "/humi_thumbnail.png",
};
---

<Layout seo={seo}>
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="mt-10 max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6">
    <a
      href="/projects"
      class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 opacity-50 hover:opacity-100 transition-opacity text-sm mb-8"
    >
      ← Back to projects
    </a>

    <p class="text-sm opacity-50 uppercase tracking-widest mb-3 font-medium">
      Case Study · HackBB 2025
    </p>
    <h1 class="font-bold text-3xl mb-4 leading-snug">
      Humi - an AI meeting assistant
    </h1>
    <a
      href="https://www.figma.com/design/zdUWixNWPkcpU9J4K3HVbx/Humi?node-id=0-1&t=hpA4Sr7tpp3SdQEn-1"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener noreferrer"
      class="group/link inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full border border-white/10 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium opacity-70 hover:opacity-100 hover:border-accent transition-all duration-300 mb-4 w-fit"
    >
      View in Figma
      <span
        aria-hidden="true"
        class="transition-transform duration-300 group-hover/link:translate-x-0.5"
        >→</span
      >
    </a>
    <p class="text-lg opacity-70 mb-8 max-w-xl leading-relaxed">
      Hi, I'm Humi. I help leaders read their team's emotions and run meetings
      so that everyone feels heard.
    </p>

    <!-- Overview grid -->
    <div
      class="grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-4 gap-4 py-6 border-t border-b border-white/10 mb-10"
    >
      <div>
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-1">My Role</p>
        <p class="text-sm font-medium">Product Designer</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-1">
          Timeline
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm font-medium">under 24 hours</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-1">
          Design Tools
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm font-medium">Figma, Lottie</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-1">
          Tech Stack
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm font-medium">Python, Avalonia UI (.NET), Llama 3.2</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Hero image -->
    <div class="rounded-xl overflow-hidden m-6 bg-gray-800">
      <!-- TODO: replace with a real screenshot of the Humi desktop app -->
      <Image
        src="/humi_thumbnail.png"
        alt="Humi desktop app showing the real-time emotion widget"
        width={1200}
        height={675}
        class="w-full object-cover"
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHALLENGE -->
  <section class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 mb-16">
    <h2 class="font-semibold text-xl mb-4">The Challenge</h2>
    <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Leaders consistently name communication as one of the hardest parts of the
      job. A struggle that gets worse in remote and online meetings, where tone
      of voice and body language are the first things lost.
    </p>
    <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed">
      The design challenge was to give leaders a way to <strong
        >read how their team is actually feeling</strong
      > in the moment.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- PROCESS -->
  <section class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 mb-16">
    <h2 class="font-semibold text-xl mb-8">Process</h2>

    <div class="space-y-12">
      <!-- Step 1 -->
      <div>
        <p
          class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-2 font-medium"
        >
          01 — Define
        </p>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-base mb-3">Helpful, not intrusive</h3>
        <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm">
          The core design tension: leaders need real-time emotional insight to
          run better meetings, but nothing about the product could feel like it
          was watching or judging the team. From keeping the experience local
          and login-free, to giving Humi a warm, character-driven personality
          rather than a dashboard feel.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 2 -->
      <div>
        <p
          class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-2 font-medium"
        >
          02 — Concept
        </p>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-base mb-3">
          From facial data to a leader's summary
        </h3>
        <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm mb-4">
          We built Humi around a model trained on FER-2013, a research dataset
          behind a paper published at the International Conference on Machine
          Learning (ICML) — 35,000 images labelled across 7 emotions (anger,
          happiness, neutral, sadness, surprise, fear, and disgust). On top of
          that, the product had two core features:
        </p>
        <ul
          class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 mb-4"
        >
          <li>
            <strong>Real-time emotion widget</strong> — a lightweight overlay that
            surfaces how the room is feeling as the meeting happens.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>AI meeting assistant</strong> — transcribes the conversation and,
            powered by Llama 3.2, generates a summary the leader can revisit afterward,
            alongside a post-meeting view of the team's sentiment and emotion trends.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <!-- TODO: replace with a screenshot of the emotion widget in use -->
        <div class="rounded-l overflow-hidden m-6 bg-gray-800">
          <Image
            src="/humi_dashboard.png"
            alt="Humi's real-time emotion widget"
            width={1200}
            height={675}
            class="w-full object-cover"
          />
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 3 -->
      <div>
        <p
          class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest opacity-40 mb-2 font-medium"
        >
          03 — Design & Prototype
        </p>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-base mb-3">Giving Humi a personality</h3>
        <p class="opacity-70 leading-relaxed text-sm mb-4">
          I designed the interface, the character of Humi, and the
          end-of-meeting summary experience in Figma, then brought Humi to life
          with animated visual assets in Lottie — small, expressive moments
          meant to make an emotion-tracking tool feel encouraging rather than
          clinical. Privacy shaped the product decisions too: we kept it as a
          simple desktop app, with no cloud storage and no login required.
        </p>
        <!-- TODO: replace with a screenshot of the Figma/Lottie assets or final prototype -->
        <div class="rounded-xl overflow-hidden m-6 bg-gray-800">
          <Image
            src="/humi_faces.png"
            alt="Humi app mockups and character design"
            width={1200}
            height={675}
            class="w-full object-cover"
          />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- NAVIGATION -->
<section
      class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 mb-16 flex justify-center items-center border-t border-white/10 pt-8"
    >
      <a
        href="/projects"
        class="opacity-50 hover:opacity-100 transition-opacity text-sm"
      >
        ← All projects
      </a>
    </section>
  </section>

  <style>
    strong {
      color: white;
      font-weight: 600;
    }
    em {
      color: inherit;
    }
  </style>
</Layout>
